Feature Engineering

What is feature engineering?

Feature engineering is the process of using domain knowledge to create features (characteristics, properties, attributes, etc.) that make machine learning algorithms work effectively. These features can be thought of as the important pieces of data that a machine learning model uses to understand the problem it's trying to solve.

Feature engineering can involve several different tasks:

  • Feature creation: This is about creating new features from existing ones. In some cases, combining two features can give a more powerful representation than keeping them as separate features. An example would be creating a 'BMI' feature from 'height' and 'weight' features in a health dataset.
  • Feature extraction: This is the process of transforming raw data into features that better represent the underlying problem to the predictive models. For example, performing text analytics to represent the text in a data set as frequencies of words or phrases.
  • Feature transformation: This is the process of changing the distribution or relationship of a feature with the target variable. Some machine learning models, like linear regression, expect a linear relationship between features and target. If that relationship naturally doesn't exist, you'd need to transform the feature. For example, you may take a log transformation of skewed data or a scaling transformation to transform data to a common scale.
  • Feature selection: This is about selecting the most important features or discarding the less important features. Some features don't contribute to the predictive power of a model and can be dropped. For example, a feature like 'customer ID' will probably have no prediction power because it's unique for every instance. Similarly, a feature that has a very high correlation or dependency with another feature may be dropped since it doesn't add new information. Feature selection is also important because it helps to reduce overfitting. The more features you have, the more likely your model will learn noise and not signal.

As for how the process is done, its often a combination of knowledge from the data domain, intuition, and a good amount of trial and error. High-quality features can often make the difference between a poorly performing model and a highly accurate predictive system. Feature engineering is usually performed via a range of techniques in your language of choice, and many of the libraries in that language can assist with this. For example, you can use libraries like pandas for feature creation, and sklearn for feature selection and transformation in Python.

Let's look into our data and see if we can create some new features.

Feature and Model selection

Adjusting the training error

  • The training error is the error of the model on the training data.
  • The test error is the error of the model on the test data.
  • The training error can be adjusted to better reflect the test error.
  • The adjusted training error is the training error plus a penalty term that increases as the number of parameters in the model increases.
  • Complexity of a model is measured by the number of parameters it uses.

Suppose you have identified a number of different variables that you may want to include in different models. Let $V$ be the set of all variables you consider. All possible combination of the variables in $V$ are in the power set $\mathcal{P}(V)$, which includes the empty set (in that case the null model - the mean) as well as $V$ itself. How can you judge which variable combination will probably perform best out-of-sample by assessing the model performance only with your available sample?

Obviously, you could choose the full model $V$ - which is probably the model producing the highest $AUC$ in-sample. Nevertheless, will it perform well out-of-sample?

There are two approaches used often in machine learning, called:

  • adjusting the training error and
  • the cross-validation approach and the application of bootstrapping

Example

Let \begin{equation*} y_i = 10 + 3x_i - 1.5z_i + \epsilon_i \end{equation*}

and let's say you have additional data represented by the matrix $\boldsymbol{K}_{N\times7}$. Can you simply include $\boldsymbol{K}$? All variables in $\boldsymbol{K}$ are independent to each other as well as with $\boldsymbol{x}$, $\boldsymbol{z}$ and $\boldsymbol{y}$.

What are your expectations when running two regression:

  1. $y$ on $x$ and $z$

  2. $y$ on $x$ and $z$ as well as all $k$

In[40]:
def generate_sample(N, seed):
    np.random.seed(seed)
    eps = np.random.normal(0,5,N)
    x = np.random.normal(10,3,N)
    z = np.random.normal(8,5,N)
    y = 10 + 3*x - 1.5*z + eps
    K = np.random.normal(0,10,size=(N,7))

    temp1 = pd.DataFrame({'y':y, 'x':x, 'z':z})
    temp2 = pd.DataFrame(K)
    temp2.columns = ['k'+str(i) for i in range(1,8)]
    return pd.concat([temp1, temp2], axis=1)


data = generate_sample(500, 223)

mdl1 = sm.OLS.from_formula('y ~ x + z + 1', data=data).fit()
mdl2 = sm.OLS.from_formula('y ~ x + z + k1 + k2 + k3 + k4 + k5 + k6 + k7 + 1', data=data).fit()

R2

  • in simple terms: variance explained by the model
  • the larger to 1, the more is explained by the model (is a value of 1 or near 1 good?)
  • R2 always increases as additional variables are added - Why?

Adj. R2

  • like R2, but "corrected" / "adjusted" for the number of parameters to estimate (degrees of freedom)
  • Idea: If you have the "optimal" model, adding some noise variables will decrease the error of the regression only marginally but increases the number of parameters (penalty)
  • R2 and adj. R2 only in OLS (Pseudo R2 exists for GLM like logit models)

AIC

  • for least squares: $AIC=\frac{1}{n\cdot \sigma_\epsilon^2} \cdot (RSS+2d\sigma_\epsilon^2)$
  • in general: $AIC=2\cdot d-2\log({\hat {L}})$
  • the lower the better

BIC

  • for least squares: $BIC=\frac{1}{n}\cdot(RSS+\log(n)d\sigma_\epsilon^2)$
  • in general: $BIC =\log(n) \cdot d - 2\cdot\ln({\hat {L}})$
  • the lower the better
  • larger penality compared to AIC, as log(n)>2 for n>7
  • hence, smaller models are recommended by the statistic

with

  • $d$ the number of variables (estimated parameters),
  • $RSS$ the residual sum of squares,
  • $n$ the number of observations,
  • $\sigma_\epsilon^2$ the estimated variance of the error term and
  • $\hat{L}$ being the the maximized value of the likelihood function of the model.

In our example dataset

Cross validation

Cross-validation is a technique for evaluating ML models by training several ML models on subsets of the available input data and evaluating them on the complementary subset of the data.

The main idea behind cross-validation is that we don't want to use all of our data for training. We want to keep some data aside to test our model on. However, we also want to make sure that we are training our model on as much data as possible. Cross-validation is a way to do both of these things.

  • repeatedly draw a random sample of size $n$ from the data set and fit the model to this sample
  • use the remaining observations to calculate the error of the model (e.g. MSE, Gini, or you favorite performance measure)
  • You get a distribution of performance observations, which you can use to calculate the mean and standard deviation, ...

There are many different cross-validation methods. The most common one is k-fold cross-validation. In k-fold cross-validation, you split the data into k equally sized subsets (or folds). You then train the model on k-1 folds and test it on the remaining fold. You repeat this procedure k times, each time using a different fold as the test set. You then average the performance over the k folds. This is called k-fold cross-validation.

Other approaches are:

  • Validation set approach: randomly split the data into two parts: a training set and a validation set. Fit the model on the training set and calculate the error on the validation set.
  • Leave-one-out cross-validation (LOOCV): k-fold cross-validation where k is equal to the number of observations in the data set.
  • Leave-p-out cross-validation (LPOCV): nearly the same as LOOCV, but you leave p observations out instead of one. This is a generalization of LOOCV. But how many different combinations of p observations are there? If you have n observations, there are n choose p combinations. This is a very large number, so LPOCV is not often used.
  • Repeated k-fold cross-validation: repeat k-fold cross-validation n times. This is useful if you want to repeat the cross-validation procedure several times to get a more accurate estimate of the performance of the model. In each repitition, the data is split into k folds in a different way.
  • Stratified k-fold cross-validation: k-fold cross-validation where the folds are selected so that the mean response value is approximately equal in all the folds. This is useful for classification problems where you have an imbalanced data set (i.e. one class is much more frequent than the other class). In this case, you want to make sure that the class proportions are approximately equal in all the folds.

Let's look at an example of k-fold cross-validation.

In[48]:
# Create the folds
kf = KFold(n_splits=200, shuffle=True, random_state=1)
tmp_df = df_train.assign(default_num=lambda x: x.default.astype(int))

# Loop over the folds
res1 = []
res2 = []

for train_index, test_index in tqdm(kf.split(tmp_df)):
    # Get the training and test sets
    df_train_fold = tmp_df.iloc[train_index]
    df_test_fold = tmp_df.iloc[test_index]
    
    # Fit the model on the training set
    model1 = smf.logit(formula=f'default_num ~ age', data=df_train_fold).fit(disp=False)
    model2 = smf.logit(formula=f'default_num ~ age + loan_purpose_auto', data=df_train_fold).fit(disp=False)
    
    # Evaluate the model on the test set
    eval1 = helpers.evaluate_model(df_test_fold.default, model1.predict(df_test_fold))
    eval2 = helpers.evaluate_model(df_test_fold.default, model2.predict(df_test_fold))
    
    # Save the results
    res1.append(eval1['gini'])
    res2.append(eval2['gini'])

There are different techniques to iterate over different combination of variables. One of them is the so called stepwise regression.

In a stepwise regression, you start with the null model (no variables) and add variables one by one. At each step, you add the variable that gives the best improvement to the model. You stop when no further improvement can be made. There are two types of stepwise regressions:

  • Forward stepwise regression: start with the null model and add variables one by one.
  • Backward stepwise regression: start with the full model and remove variables one by one.
  • Hybrid stepwise regression: a combination of forward and backward stepwise regression.

Besides that, there are other techniques to select variables, for example:

  • Regularized regression models (e.g. logit regressions with L1 / L2 penalty called Lasso / Ridge Regressions too)
    • Lasso regression: L1 penalty means that the sum of the absolute values of the coefficients is penalized. This leads to some coefficients being exactly equal to zero. This means that some variables are completely excluded from the model. This is useful for variable selection.
    • Ridge regression: L2 penalty means that the sum of the squared values of the coefficients is penalized. This leads to some coefficients being very small, but not exactly equal to zero. This means that all variables are included in the model, but some variables have a very small effect on the response variable.
  • Tree based models like random forests
  • ...

Using cross-validation, you can not only select the best combination of variables, but also the "best model".

Model selection

Using cross-validation, we can not only select the best combination of variables, but also the best model. In our example, we have two different models - both based on a logistic regression framework, but one includes an additional variable. Instead of using a logistic regression, you could also use a different approach, for example:

  • random forest classifier,
  • gradient boosting classifier,
  • XGBoost classifier,
  • neural network,
  • ...

Overfitting

In the previous example, the variables in the matrix $\boldsymbol{K}$ were not correlated with each other or the other variables by construction. Nevertheless, due to randomness / luck / misfortune, $\boldsymbol{k}_2$ was already significant in the regression using the full sample.

Such spurious relationships - relationships that only hold in-sample, but not out-of-sample - are very common in general. Furthermore, some variables may provide some information about the probability of default, but the information content will be too low if other aspects of the variable, which will distort your performance, are taken into account. Think about how many different ratio of balance sheet, P&L and cash flow items you could create.

But how can you decide if a variable is useful or not, especially with respect the case study?

  1. economic reasoning
  2. economic reasoning
  3. economic reasoning

Of course, that is not all - you can for example:

  • Evaluate each variable of interest alone w.r.t. its prediction power of defaults.
    • Nevertheless, remember that there some variables may not be directly important, but only in combination with another variable.
    • Hence, only looking at p-values and / or a Gini coefficient is not enough, especially in an univariate context.
    • Try to visualize the differences in the distribution of the variables depending on wheather they default or not.
  • Identify variables that include nearly the same information - if they include the same information, you will not need both of them - use one or combination (e.g. Dimension Reduction Methods like PCA)
  • Use some machine learning techniques, for example:
  • Stepwise regressions (Forward, Backward, Hybrid)
  • Regularized regressions models (e.g. logit regressions with L1 / L2 penalty called Lasso / Ridge Regressions too)
  • Tree based models like random forests
In[50]:
y = df_train.default.astype(int)
cols_x = list(df_train.columns.drop('default'))
X = df_train[cols_x]

mdl = tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini', random_state=100,
                                  max_features=None,
                                  min_samples_split=10,
                                  min_samples_leaf=5, max_depth=20)

mdl.fit(X,y)
p = mdl.predict_proba(X)[:,1]

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(35, 15))
tree.plot_tree(mdl, max_depth=3, fontsize=15, feature_names=cols_x, proportion=True,
               filled=True, rounded=True)
plt.show()
In[51]:
print(tree.export_text(mdl, feature_names=cols_x, spacing=3, decimals=1, show_weights=True))

Feature importance in a tree-based model refers to a numerical measure that describes the contributory worth of each feature in the prediction of the target variable. In tree-based models like Decision Trees, Random Forests, and Gradient Boosting Machines, feature importance is calculated as the total reduction in the model's impurity or error brought by that feature, also known as the Gini importance.

For a decision trees, each node in the tree is a condition on a specific feature, designed to split the dataset into two so that similar response values end up in the same set. The measure of impurity (Gini index, entropy, etc.) depends upon the task being solved (classification, regression, etc.). The importance of a feature is computed as the (normalized) total reduction of the criterion brought by that feature.

In[52]:
imp = pd.Series(mdl.feature_importances_,index=cols_x).sort_values(ascending=False)
plt.figure(figsize=(15,10))
imp[imp>0].plot.barh(color="black").invert_yaxis();

In sample ROC for Tree

In[53]:
pdpred = mdl.predict_proba(X)[:,1]

fpr, tpr, thresholds = sk.metrics.roc_curve(df_train.default, pdpred)
auc = metrics.auc(fpr, tpr)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,5))
lw = 2
axes = plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkred',
                lw=lw, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % auc)
axes = plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='lightblue', lw=lw, linestyle='--')
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic example - In sample')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()

print('AUC:  ',auc)
print('GINI: ', 2*auc -1)

AUC:   0.9557647148113855
GINI:  0.911529429622771

Out of sample ROC for Tree

Logistic regressions aren't without any alternative. There are many interesting candidates you could try out, but I will be very happy with a logistic regressions. Don't forget the story of the case study and don't assume that the people you have to explain your approach, like the CRO, are machine learning experts. A CRO will want to understand what you have done and simply copy some code you found in the world wide web to estimate a fancy super model without understanding it will not be enough. Furthermore, many people in a bank will want to be able to understand the effect of X on Y - and many people have problems to comprehend non-linear relationships. Furthermore, you will prefer a robust model and given the number of observations in your dataset finding a well out-of-sample performing logistic regression model will be difficult enough.

Due to that, I will not go into any details about the below listed methods. Nevertheless, such models are very interesting on their own and if you are able to explain me those models and provide me with an economic reasoning of your results, you are welcome to use them of course.

  • Ensambling methods (Boosting and Bagging)
  • Generalized Additive Models
  • Support Vector and Gradient Boosting Machines
  • Random Forests and other tree based models
  • Neural networks
  • ...
